     I'm just wondering how it is that yall have 'wasted money on software' in the past.  Do you just go to the store, read the back of the box, and buy the game?  I would think that is a bad idea.  Lets go back to the car analogy.  Lets say you are buying a car.  Do you not seek out external opinions on the car?  Ask your friends how it drives?  Ask other owners if thiers was in the shop constantly?  Why would you waste $50.00 on a 1 in 100 chance at buying something that you enjoy?  For that matter, why try out games that you are nearly 100 percent sure suck ass?  There's tons and tons of non-biased game review joints both on the web and in printed magazines.  I'm just a little confused here as to why you would rather break a law... a law which you believe to be correct... rather than reading about what other people think about the game? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/umartif.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Martif</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 383<br> <font color=#333333>(6/27/02 4:43:24 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fnamelesstavernrantsandflames.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2735.topic&index=150>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> 10sun :(</span><hr size=1> <br>
   Bro, you cant really blame the developers because your machine has some type of anomoly.  I do believe that microsoft should allow you to return the game(s) though.  If they fail to help you, and you have a standard hardware configuration, they should stand behind thier product.  That being said, however, MW4 works like a champ on 10's of 1000's of computers.  I'd say at a very minimum, it works fine on 50,000 computers.  You just happen to have some type of issue.  It could be your video card, or your video drivers, or your memory, or just about anything else.  Have you tried any intensive stuff to check the condition of your system.  I can recommend a few things.  Firstly, a piece of software called Sandra tests cpu bandwidth, memory bandwidth, etc..etc.  Secondly, a utility called memtest86 will brutally test your memory.  It is one bootable floppy, and is free.  Another tool that can sometimes at least force crashes for testing purposes is 3dmarkSE.  You might also do a surface scan on your<br>
harddrive with scandisk.  I know, it seems like alot to do to play a game, but...   Take a look at the PS2, or the Xbox, or any *recent* console.  How many lockup problems do you see?  How many buggy games?  Ya know why?  Because the hardware is roughly identical between consoles of the same type.  Unfortunately, the PC platform is somewhat of a moving target, where 3rd parties are writing drivers, other 3rd partys are writing games, other 3rd parties are making random hardware, etc..etc..  Its a god damned miracle that they work as well as they do...<br>
<br>
   Anyway, good luck if you try any of the things that I listed above, 10sun.<br>
<br>
